<p>
  Text case conversion is one of the most common everyday tasks for writers, developers, data analysts, and SEO professionals. Whether you're formatting a headline, naming a variable, building a URL slug, or cleaning messy imported data, knowing which case style to use — and how to convert between them quickly — saves real time.
</p>

<h2>The 8 Most Common Text Case Types</h2>

<h3>1. lowercase</h3>
<p>Every letter is lowercase. Used for: general text, email addresses, URLs, CSS properties.</p>
<p>Example: <code>the quick brown fox</code></p>

<h3>2. UPPERCASE</h3>
<p>Every letter is a capital. Used for: acronyms, abbreviations, shouting in informal text, database column names in some conventions.</p>
<p>Example: <code>THE QUICK BROWN FOX</code></p>

<h3>3. Title Case</h3>
<p>Principal words are capitalized; articles, short prepositions, and conjunctions are lowercase. Used for: book titles, article headlines, formal document headings, navigation labels.</p>
<p>Example: <code>The Quick Brown Fox Jumps Over the Lazy Dog</code></p>

<h3>4. Sentence case</h3>
<p>Only the first word and proper nouns are capitalized. Used for: blog headings, casual writing, most modern web content.</p>
<p>Example: <code>The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog</code></p>

<h3>5. camelCase</h3>
<p>No spaces; each word after the first starts with uppercase. Used for: JavaScript variables and functions, Java class members, API response field names.</p>
<p>Example: <code>theQuickBrownFox</code></p>

<h3>6. PascalCase</h3>
<p>Like camelCase, but the first word is also capitalized. Used for: class names in most programming languages (JavaScript, TypeScript, C#, Java), React component names.</p>
<p>Example: <code>TheQuickBrownFox</code></p>

<h3>7. snake_case</h3>
<p>All lowercase with underscores between words. Used for: Python variables and functions, Ruby methods, database column names, file names on Unix systems.</p>
<p>Example: <code>the_quick_brown_fox</code></p>

<h3>8. kebab-case</h3>
<p>All lowercase with hyphens between words. Used for: URL slugs, HTML/CSS class names, HTML data attributes, file names in web projects.</p>
<p>Example: <code>the-quick-brown-fox</code></p>

<h2>Quick Reference: Which Case Style for What</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Book/film titles:</strong> Title Case</li>
  <li><strong>Blog headings (modern style):</strong> Sentence case</li>
  <li><strong>URL slugs:</strong> kebab-case</li>
  <li><strong>CSS class names:</strong> kebab-case</li>
  <li><strong>JavaScript variables:</strong> camelCase</li>
  <li><strong>JavaScript class names:</strong> PascalCase</li>
  <li><strong>Python variables:</strong> snake_case</li>
  <li><strong>Database columns:</strong> snake_case</li>
  <li><strong>Acronyms (NASA, CEO):</strong> UPPERCASE</li>
  <li><strong>Email subject lines:</strong> Sentence case or Title Case</li>
</ul>

